      <!-- Modal Header -->
      <div class="modal-header">
        <h5 class="modal-title" id="caterpillarModalLabel">Canibalistic Caterpillars Model</h5>
        <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close"></button>
      </div>
      
      <!-- Modal Body with scrolling and flex-grow -->
      <div class="modal-body overflow-auto flex-grow-1">
        <p> An inquiry into dynamic changes to the population of butterflies given initial resource (food, population, growth rate, etc) allocation.</p>

        <p>This project is a python implementation of a commonly used population dynamic model (often shown on the example of population of foxes vs. rabbits). The model runs the simulation and outputs a .csv file with relevant information.</p>
        
        <b>Motivation:</b>
        <p>In the nature, some species of caterpillars are known to be canibalistic. The model is a simulation of such behavior. The model is based on the Lotka-Volterra equations, which describe the dynamics of biological systems in which two species interact, one as a predator and the other as prey.</p>
        <p>In this case, the caterpillars are both the prey and the preditor. The model simulates the population dynamics of both species over time, taking into account factors such as birth rates, death rates, and the availability of resources (leaves).</p>
        <p>The model is implemented in Python and uses the NumPy library for numerical calculations. The simulation runs for a specified number of iterations, and the results are stored in a CSV file for further analysis.</p>
        <p>The model can be used to study the effects of different parameters on the population dynamics of the caterpillars and leaves, such as the initial population sizes, growth rates, and carrying capacities. </p>
        <p>Overall, this project provides a valuable tool for understanding the complex interactions between species in an ecosystem and the factors that influence their population dynamics.</p>
      </div>
      
